The rotation matrix for \(90^\circ\) clockwise is: \[ \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \] - Multiply this matrix by the translated point \((-4, -3)\): \[ \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \cdot (-4) + 1 \cdot (-3) \\ -1 \cdot (-4) + 0 \cdot (-3) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \] 3. **Translate back to the original coordinate system**: - Add the center of rotation \((3, 1)\) to the rotated point \((-3, 4)\): \[ (-3 + 3, 4 + 1) = (0, 5) \] 4. **Calculate the sum of the coordinates**: - The new coordinates are \((0, 5)\). The sum of the x and y coordinates is: \[ 0 + 5 = 5 \] Thus, the sum of the x and y coordinates of the new position is \(\boxed{5}\).
